article.description: Robert Jackson scored 26 points as 12th-ranked Marquette pulled away from the Tigers in the second half en route to a 105-74 triumph.
article.headline: Jackson scores season-high 26 points
article.linkText: Jackson's best game of season leads Marquette's rout
article.story: MILWAUKEE (AP) -- The Marquette Golden Eagles (No. 12 ESPN/USA Today, No. 13 AP) got a second chance to make a good first impression. Marquette routed Grambling State 105-74 Saturday in the first game between the schools behind a season-high 26 points from Robert Jackson, 23 from Dwyane Wade and a career-best 16 from Todd Townsend. The Golden Eagles (8-1) stumbled from the start, however, turning the ball over 11 times in the first half and leading just 39-37 with 4:21 left in the half. After taking a 53-45 halftime lead, Marquette opened the second half on a 26-4 run to ice its 23rd straight victory at home. "We ran the same press offense as we did in the first half, we just did it better in the second half,'' Golden Eagles coach Tom Crean said. Townsend said the Golden Eagles were taken aback by the Tigers' quickness and athleticism before taking advantage of their soft defense for easy baskets. "We didn't know they were that quick,'' he said. "You really don't see their quickness on film. They got to us early with the press. We made a couple of mental mistakes.'' For the first 15 minutes, the game looked like a YMCA free-for-all as the Golden Eagles fell into the Tigers' up-tempo trap and made too many mistakes on both ends of the court. Back-to-back 3-pointers by Ron Ellis pulled Grambling State to 39-37 before Marquette closed the first half with a 14-6 run for a 53-45 lead at the break. Their 26-4 spurt to start the second half made it 79-49, and Crean emptied his bench as the Golden Eagles tied their Bradley Center record for points scored and set their record at the arena with 29 assists. Paul Haynes' 21 points and Brion Rush's 17 led the Tigers (3-7), who have dropped four straight and were outrebounded 45-26. "They wore us down,'' Tigers coach Larry Wright said. "We have two big guys. They have six. That was the story of the ballgame. "I told them to hold their heads up. I told them to remember the first 20 minutes and not the last 20 minutes.'' Which is exactly the opposite of what the Golden Eagles want. The Golden Eagles got off to a rocky start that included a scary spill over the scorer's table by Wade and an uncharacteristic horrid stretch by point guard Travis Diener. After badly mistiming an alley-oop pass to Wade for a turnover, Diener had a foul and two traveling calls within a minute and took a seat with 15:25 left in the first half. But Diener settled down, as did the rest of the Golden Eagles. He had a 3-pointer, a fastbreak layup and two assists to Jackson in the opening minutes of the second half and finished with 12 points, nine assists and five defensive rebounds. "After not having a great first half, we did an excellent job in the second half of attacking the pressure,'' Crean said. "Anytime you assist on 29 of 39 field goals, it is quite impressive.'' Crean scheduled just one game over the last two weeks for finals and a holiday break, and he said the first half was a result of rust. "We took some time off and our conditioning wasn't where it should be in the first half,'' he said. "Once we did start playing and taking care of the ball, we saw a lot of good things take place in the second half. We got a lot of good basketball out of a lot of guys.''
